      "text": "Let's say you detect a low-to-high transition at 2.5 V. A 100 mV hysteresis would mean that the low-to-high transition is detected at 2.55 V and the high-to-low transition is detected at 2.45 V, a 100 mV [[Difference]]. [https://electronics.stackexchange.com/questions/12312/what-is-input-hysteresis stackexchange]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a18a2053aa30f960",
      "text": "Hysteresis is used to prevent several quickly successive changes if the input signal would contain some noise, for example. The noise could mean you cross the threshold of 2.5 V more than just once, which you don't want. "
    },
